      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "On one side (Figure 1A1), it is possible to start directly from unaligned samples to construct a sample's MEMO vector (Figure 1B). In this case, the only required input is a. mgf file for each sample (Mascot Generic Format, a text format commonly used to report fragmentation mass spectrometry data) containing all the sample's features MS/MS spectra... Documents are then aggregated by summing peaks and losses occurrences across spectra of a given sample to obtain the MEMO vector (Figure 1B). Samples' MEMO vectors can then be aligned to obtain a MEMO matrix (Figure 1C). This way of building a MEMO matrix without prior RT based features alignment across samples is defined hereafter as 'MEMO from unaligned samples' approach (Figure 1A1).",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes the 'MEMO from unaligned samples' workflow and the generation of MEMO vectors and matrices from unaligned MS2 spectra.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3389-fbinf-2022-842964",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Does the memo_from_unaligned component correctly generate a MemoMatrix object with the expected structure and content when applied to unaligned MS2 spectra files?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:57:13.656849+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "First, MS2 spectra are filtered and binned using matchms and spec2vec packages: peaks and losses to the precursor of the spectrum are converted into words (i.e. peak@mz and loss@mz) and grouped into so-called documents (Huber et al., 2020; Huber et al., 2021). Documents are then aggregated by summing peaks and losses occurrences across spectra of a given sample to obtain the MEMO vector (Figure 1B). Samples' MEMO vectors can then be aligned to obtain a MEMO matrix (Figure 1C).",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes the MEMO matrix as a structured output containing aggregated peak and loss counts (words) indexed by sample.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3389-fbinf-2022-842964",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
